maneuverable capabilities in the support of the Navy's Fleet Design and Distributed Maritime Operations concepts through its primary missions: Intelligence,
Surveillance, Reconnaissance & Targeting (ISR&T), Antisubmarine Warfare, Surface Warfare (SUW), Electronic Warfare, Command and Control, and Non-Combat
Operations. Secondary missions include: Amphibious Warfare, Air Warfare, Health Services, Fleet Support - Operations, Logistics, and Naval Special Warfare (NSW).
Primary missions of the MH-60S include Combat Logistics, SUW, NSW, Combat Search and Rescue, and Airborne Mine Countermeasures. Additional missions include
counter-Unmanned Aerial Systems (cUAS), ISR&T, Search and Rescue, Humanitarian Assistance and Defense Support for Civil Authorities.

 1709: The 25+ year old MH-60 platform is facing significant obsolescence issues that cannot be affordably addressed in a timely manner by traditional, line-by-line
 mitigation methods. The Service Life Modernization (SLM) plan will develop the Tailorable Architecture Leveraging Open-systems for Navy (TALON) upgrade that
 resolves multiple obsolescence issues within the flight critical avionics and mission systems. TALON will enable a rapid response to emerging threats and fleet
 requirements ensuring the MH-60 continues to be a relevant, supportable, and cost-effective platform. This approach will allow for faster replacement of obsolete
 equipment at less cost by increasing competition. Additionally, the intent is a for TALON to be portable to future platforms, such as the Future Vertical Lift (Maritime
 Strike) program, mitigating future cost and schedule.




