Title: Demonstration Rocket for Agile Cislunar Operations (DRACO)                                                                      73.216     76.732              -
Description: Maintaining U.S. interests in cislunar space requires significant advances in propulsion technology. Current
space propulsion includes electric (high efficiency but low thrust) and chemical (high thrust but low efficiency) systems. The
Demonstration Rocket for Agile Cislunar Operations (DRACO) program will develop and demonstrate a High-Assay Low-Enriched
Uranium (HALEU) nuclear thermal rocket (NTR) system on orbit and is targeting an FY 2027 launch. The NTR technology
demonstrated by DRACO will achieve thrust similar to chemical rockets, but with 2-5 times the efficiency. The enhanced
performance afforded by NTR will allow the U.S. to lead operations in the cislunar volume, in particular for missions that require
flexible mission planning and agile maneuverability.

Beginning in FY 2026, this program will be funded in PE 0603468E, Project ACX-01.

FY 2025 Plans:
- Complete fabrication of long lead components for the DRACO spacecraft.
- Conduct reactor cold-flow test.
- Begin manufacture of first-ever HALEU ceramic-metallic reactor core fuel assemblies.
- Complete spacecraft propulsion subsystem critical design review.
- Complete software subsystem critical design review.
- Begin reactor vessel and beryllium structure for reactor moderator and reflector.
- Complete acquisition and machining of remaining major NTR engine (NTRE) materials and components.
- Complete detailed design of the DRACO demonstration spacecraft.
- Begin assembly of major DRACO spacecraft subsystems and begin preparations for space environment testing.
- Conduct component level space environment testing of DRACO spacecraft subsystems.
- Complete qualification testing of the reactor flight safety device.
- Begin assembly of the fueled nuclear reactor.
- Begin full assembly of the DRACO spacecraft.
- Begin technology transition to NASA.
