Title: Prototype phase contract activity for Opposing Forces Mechanized Vehicle Replacement (OMVR)                                         3.786       5.423          13.640
Description: The Opposing Forces Mechanized Vehicle Replacement (OMVR) will consist of a common Army tracked platform
that uses modular visual modifications (VISMODs). This capability will allow the Opposing Forces to replicate five of the six
warfighting functions. This replication will train Army units to synchronize all Intelligence, Surveillance, and Reconnaissance (ISR)
assets available to the Brigade Combat Rotational Training Unit (RTU) across the depth and breadth of the CTC training area, and
provide the Opposing Force (OPFOR) and the Army with a sustainable system that is safe for Soldiers to operate and maintain.

FY 2026 Plans:
Funding will be used to initiate design, development and integration on two (2) of nine (9) Visual Modifications (VISMODS)
variants. Efforts will also include Soldier touchpoints and preliminary design review.
FY 2027 Plans:
Funding will be used to complete the design, development of the Infantry Fighting Vehicle (IFV) and Main Battle Tank (MBT) visual
modification (VISMOD) variants and initiate prototyping of four additional threat vehicles. This development directly supports Army
senior leader guidance to rapidly and accurately replicate threat force ground systems at the Combat Training Centers (CTC)
creating a realistic and immersive training environment.
FY 2026 to FY 2027 Increase/Decrease Statement:
Increase due to acceleration of prototype development from 24 to 9 months for priority VISMOD variants that will create a
significantly enhanced and modernized portrayal of opposing force mechanized and tracked vehicles to replicate the operational
environment at CTCs. FY2027 development will focus initially on Infantry Fighting Vehicle (IFV) & Main Battle Tank (MBT) design,
which represents the greatest threat in force-on-force training. Additional prototyping development will include threat support
vehicles that will provide additional challenges to the rotational training unit. These VISMODs will include Command and Control$$, $$$$, $$Competitive development efforts based on performance specifications.

 1. Combat Training Center Instrumentation Systems (CTC-IS) will leverage multiple contract vehicles to award their RDTE efforts to include: Assisted Acquisition
 Services (AAS) Defense, Consolidated Product-line Management (CPM) Plus, Live Training, Ranges, and Combat Training Centers (LTRaC) and Defense Logistics
 Agency (DLA).

 2. In FY 2020, CTIA awarded a new competitive IDIQ contract with a 1-year base and 7 single-year option periods to General Dynamics Mission Systems to continue to
 provide the common architecture for 22 live training systems at 200+ training locations worldwide.

