B. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                     FY 2025     FY 2026        FY 2027
Title: Engineering and Manufacturing Development (EMD) phase contract activity for the Common Training Instrumentation                      2.579       2.563          3.303
Architecture (CTIA) program.
Description: Continue EMD phase contract activities for the CTIA program to provide common architecture capabilities essential
for development, fielding, technology and capability insertion for 23 Live Training Systems at 200+ training locations worldwide

FY 2026 Plans:
Funding will continue the development of high priority backlog items, such as decoupling IDs to remove unnecessary
dependencies between services. Additionally, funding will support updates to the CTIA 2D map to MIL-STD-2525D and integrate
Artificial Intelligence/Machine Learning (AI/ML) into the live training ranges to assist the range support personnel. Lastly, funding
will establish enterprise level business processes and services enabling CTIA to efficiently develop, operate, and secure
capabilities in accordance with OSW Digital Engineering and Army Digital Transformations Strategies. Efforts will promote
synergies between the training and testing enablers to improve product development, integration, and cyber activities, and to
promote re-use of common assets and services to Army modernization priorities.
FY 2027 Plans:
Funding will continue the development of high priority backlog items, such as the backup/restore/purge/archive capability to make
it easier to import and export training event data. Additionally, funding will support updates to the CTIA Platform Development Kit
(PDK) and Distributed Interactive Simulation (DIS) Entity and Munition Type enumerations to maintain interoperability with Virtual/
Constructive simulations. Funding will also support planned tech insertion and concurrency tasks that are annually executed to
remain relevant to modernized technology, address pipeline inefficiencies and mitigate potential interface issues with program
software upgrades. Lastly, funding will support the execution of enterprise level business processes and services enabling CTIA to
efficiently develop, operate, and secure capabilities in accordance with OSW Digital Engineering and Army Digital Transformations
Strategies. Efforts will promote synergies between the training and testing enablers to improve product development, integration,
and cyber activities, and to promote re-use of common assets and services to Army modernization priorities.
FY 2026 to FY 2027 Increase/Decrease Statement:
FY 2027 funding increase due to increased development of high priority backlog items as well as updates to the CTIA Platform
Development Kit (PDK) and Distributed Interactive Simulation (DIS) Entity and Munition Type enumerations.
